  {
    "id": "chunk_03_persona_EXPERIENCED_SYSADMIN",
    "chunk_id": 3,
    "chunk_title": "Password requirements",
    "source_file": "02-password-requirements.md",
    "persona": "EXPERIENCED_SYSADMIN",
    "question": "What specific strings are checked against the password to classify it as weak — does it include the tenant name and user email?",
    "expected_answerable": true,
    "agent_answer": "Yes, based on the documentation, passwords that repeat **any** of the following are **always considered weak**, regardless of length:\n\n1. **User name**\n2. **Login**\n3. **User email** ✅\n4. **Tenant name** (the name of the tenant to which the user account belongs) ✅\n5. **Most common passwords** (commonly known/leaked passwords)\n\nSo to directly answer your question: **yes**, both the **tenant name** and **user email** are explicitly checked against the password, and matching any of them will classify the password as weak — even if it otherwise meets length requirements.\n\nAdditionally, weak passwords cannot be saved at all. Only medium or strong passwords are accepted.\n\n> **Source:** `02-password-requirements.md` — *Getting Started with Cyber Protection*",
