    "question": "I heard that the 'Trust this browser' checkbox is recommended to be enabled for better security. Is that correct?",
    "expected_answerable": true,
    "agent_answer": "**No, that is not correct.** In fact, it's the opposite.\n\nBased on the Acronis Cyber Protect Cloud documentation on **Two-factor authentication (2FA)**, the \"Trust this browser\" checkbox is a **convenience feature**, not a security enhancement. When you check \"Trust this browser,\" it **skips the one-time code (second factor) prompt** on that specific browser for subsequent logins (typically for 30 days).\n\nThis effectively **reduces your security** because:\n\n- 2FA is designed so that even if someone discovers your login and password, they **cannot access your account** without the one-time code from your authenticator app.\n- By trusting a browser, you remove that second layer of protection on that device — meaning anyone with access to your credentials and that browser could log in **without the one-time code**.\n\n**Recommendation for better security:**\n- **Do NOT** check \"Trust this browser,\" especially on shared or less-secure devices.\n- Always require the one-time code from your authenticator application for every login.\n\nThe \"Trust this browser\" option should only be used on personal, well-secured devices where convenience is prioritized over maximum security.\n\n📄 *Source: 03-two-factor-authentication.md — Getting Started with Cyber Protection*",
    "retrieved_chunks": [
      "03-two-factor-authentication.md",
      "10c-supported-features-antivirus-antimalware.md",
      "10d-supported-features-edr-vulnerability-patch.md"
